In what has become known as '''Gerard's conspiracy''', a group of [[Cavaliers|Royalists]] conspired to assassinate England's [[Lord Protector (Cromwell)|Lord Protector]] [[Oliver Cromwell]] in May 1654. It was discovered before an assassination attempt could be made and the Protectorate arrested about forty men. Three were tried for high treason.  A ring-leader, [[John Gerard (Royalist)|John Gerard]], was found guilty and executed, as was [[Peter Vowell]]. [[Summerset Fox]] pleaded guilty and was sentenced to transportation.{{sfn|Keightley|1841|pp=127–128}}{{sfn|Mills|2011}} The view of the Royalists and their sympathisers was that the conspirators had fallen into a trap set by Cromwell.{{sfn|Bradley|1890|p=223}}

==History==
Early in 1654 John Gerard went over to France, where he was presented to [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] by his cousin, [[Charles Gerard, 1st Earl of Macclesfield|Charles Gerard, Lord Brandon]]. Soon after his return to England in May 1654,<ref name=Bradley>{{harvnb|Bradley|1890|p=223}} cites ''State Papers'', Dom. 1654, pp. 219, 233–40, 274–436.</ref> a scheme to assassinate the Lord Protector [[Oliver Cromwell]] on his way to [[Hampton Court]] was discovered. About forty people, among whom were [[Aubrey de Vere, 20th Earl of Oxford|Aubrey, Earl of Oxford]], the two Ashburnhams ([[John Ashburnham (Royalist)|John]] and [[William Ashburnham (Royalist)|William]]), [[Sir Richard Willis, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Willis]], John Gerard and his elder brother Sir [[Sir Gilbert Gerard, 1st Baronet of Fiskerton|Gilbert]], were arrested.{{sfn|Keightley|1841|pp=127–128}}

It was alleged that in company with a Royalist major, one Henshaw (whom Gerard had met in France), Gerard with 30 other mounted men were to attack the Lord Protector, as he rode to [[Hampton Court]], and, after overwhelming his bodyguard and killing him, to besiege Whitehall,<ref name=Bradley/> seize the [[Tower of London]], and proclaim Charles II king.{{sfn|Bradley|1890|p=223}}

==Trial and punishment==
Only three men, John Gerard,  Peter Vowell (a schoolmaster) and Summerset Fox were brought to trial before the High Court of Justice.{{sfn|Mills|2011}}

The trial began on 3 June. Fox pleaded guilty (and was sentenced to transportation to [[Barbados]]{{sfn|Mills|2011}}). The other two were convicted on the evidence of ten of their accomplices, one of whom was Gerard's brother Charles, a youth of nineteen, he himself being but twenty-two.{{sfn|Keightley|1841|p=128}} Gerard declared that he had been to Paris on private business, and that Charles II had desired his friends not to engage in plots. The reluctant evidence of his younger brother Charles, to whom he sent his forgiveness from the scaffold, pointed to treasonable conversations with Henshaw and the rest in taverns.{{sfn|Bradley|1890|pp=223–224}}

Gerard and Vowell were sentenced to death by hanging. Vowell was hanged, but Gerard successfully petitioned to be beheaded instead.{{sfn|Bradley|1890|p=223}} Gerard died with undaunted courage on 10 July 1654 at [[Tower Hill]],{{sfn|Bradley|1890|pp=223–224}} avowing his Royalism, but denying all participation in the conspiracy.{{sfn|Keightley|1841|p=128}}

The Royalist writers published a copy of his prepared speech, and affirmed that he fell into a trap set by Cromwell.{{sfn|N.D.|1680|pp=147–149}} This view has been elaborately restated by Reginald Palgrave in the ''English Historical Review'' for October 1888, in the course of a controversy between that writer and [[C. H. Firth]]. However, no certain proof has been adduced of Cromwell's complicity.{{sfn|Bradley|1890|p=223}}

