{{For|the earlier white working class party|Labour Party (South Africa)}}
{{Politics of South Africa}}
The '''Labour Party''' ({{lang-af|Arbeidersparty}}) was a [[South Africa]]n political party founded in 1969 and led for many years by [[Allan Hendrickse]]. Although avowedly opposed to [[apartheid]], it participated in the [[Coloured Persons Representative Council]].<ref name="Guardian">[https://www.theguardian.com/southafrica/story/0,13262,1442366,00.html Allan Hendrickse's obituary in ''The Guardian''.]</ref> It opposed the guerrilla struggle of [[Umkhonto we Sizwe]] and the call for international sanctions against South Africa. The party later dominated the [[House of Representatives of South Africa|House of Representatives]] in the [[Tricameral Parliament]] from its foundation in 1984 until 1992, winning 76 of the 80 seats in the [[South African general election, 1984|1984 elections]] and 69 in [[South African general election, 1989|those of 1989]]. When the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] of [[Frederik Willem de Klerk|F. W. de Klerk]] decided to admit non-White members, however, a substantial number of members of the House of Representatives who had been members of Labour [[Crossing the floor|crossed the floor]] to join the Nationalists. In 1992, a group of 36 such former Labour members led by [[Jac Rabie]] engineered a vote of no confidence in Hendrickse's Labour government.<ref name="Wren">[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE5DE163DF93AA35751C0A964958260 South Africans of Mixed Race in a Political Shift.] Christopher Wren, ''[[New York Times]]'', 9 February 1992.</ref> Losing influence at the polls, Hendrickse concluded that the Labour Party had fulfilled its uses, and the party was disbanded in 1994, with Hendrickse and his followers joining the [[African National Congress]].<ref name="Baobab">[http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/orders_list.asp?show=197 Recipients of the Order of the Baobab in Silver.]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} The Presidency of South Africa.</ref>

The name of the [[New Labour Party (South Africa)|New Labour Party]] of [[Peter Marais]] was meant to evoke Hendrickse's Labour Party. It is not to be confused with the earlier [[Labour Party (South Africa)]], which had represented White industrial workers.

